<h2>When Clay Wins</h2>
<div class="guide-tool-card">
  <div class="guide-tool-header">
    <div>
      <div class="guide-tool-rank">Best for enrichment at scale</div>
      <h3 class="guide-tool-name">Clay</h3>
      <p class="guide-tool-tagline">Waterfall enrichment across 50+ data sources with AI research agents</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="guide-tool-body">
    <p>Clay is not a prospecting tool in the traditional sense — it's an enrichment and research automation platform. You bring your own lead list (from Apollo, LinkedIn Sales Navigator, or a CSV), and Clay enriches it with data from 50+ sources in a waterfall sequence, stopping when it finds a valid result.</p>
    <p>The result is significantly higher data accuracy and the ability to build hyper-personalized outreach at scale — things like pulling a prospect's recent LinkedIn posts, their company's latest funding round, or job openings that signal buying intent.</p>
    <h4>Choose Clay if:</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>You're running high-volume outbound (1,000+ leads/month)</li>
      <li>Data accuracy and deliverability are your primary bottlenecks</li>
      <li>You want to build personalization at scale (not just mail merge)</li>
      <li>You have a RevOps or growth engineer to build the workflows</li>
      <li>You're already using Apollo or LinkedIn Sales Nav as your data source</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Clay's real limitations:</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>No built-in sequencing — you need Instantly, Outreach, or Salesloft to send</li>
      <li>Steep learning curve — expect 2–4 weeks before you're productive</li>
      <li>Credit-based pricing can get expensive at high volume</li>
      <li>Overkill for teams sending fewer than 500 emails/month</li>
    </ul>
